# Fishing Copilot — Cursor Rules

## Stack
Python 3.12+, Claude Haiku 4.5 Batch API, SQLite, Twilio, GitHub Actions, pytest, ruff

## Conventions
- Use `dataclass(frozen=True)` or `NamedTuple` for all data structures
- Use parameterized SQL queries — never f-string SQL
- Use `logging` with structured JSON output — no print statements
- Use type hints on all function signatures
- Keep functions under 50 lines, files under 400 lines
- Use immutable patterns: return new objects, never mutate
- Store all LLM prompt templates in `src/fishing_copilot/llm/prompts.py`
- Use content hashing (SHA-256) for report dedup
- Validate all external API responses before storing

## File Patterns
- Collectors (API clients): `src/fishing_copilot/collectors/`
- Scrapers (HTML): `src/fishing_copilot/scrapers/`
- LLM pipeline: `src/fishing_copilot/llm/`
- Delivery: `src/fishing_copilot/delivery/`
- Tests mirror source: `tests/test_collectors/`, `tests/test_scrapers/`, etc.

## Testing
- Framework: pytest + responses (HTTP mocking)
- Write tests FIRST, then implementation
- Mock all HTTP calls in unit tests
- Use saved HTML fixtures for scraper tests
- Tag real API tests with `@pytest.mark.integration`
- Coverage target: 80%+

## Key Patterns
- Two-pass LLM: extract (HTML→JSON), then synthesize (data→briefing)
- LLM-as-resilience-layer: Haiku extracts semantically even when HTML structure changes
- Process once, deliver many: LLM cost is fixed regardless of user count
- Graceful degradation: pipeline continues when individual sources fail
